(iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Mogadishu - The head of the African Union mission in Somalia is seeking a surge in troops to help the country's security forces control areas won back from the extremist group al-Shabaab.Francisco Caetano Madeira says the Somalia National Army has been unable to take full charge of areas liberated by the 22 000-strong multinational AU force, as had been expected.The request for an unspecified number of additional AU troops comes amid widespread concern that Somalia's military will not be ready to take over the country's security as the AU force prepares to withdraw by the end of 2020."It's time we made it known that AMISOM is not going to stay forever," Madeira told a high-level AU meeting Thursday.Al-Shabaab continues to carry out deadly attacks in Somalia.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.